               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18390617-name-1444" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18390617-name-1444" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18390617-name-1444" type="surname" value="CROSSLEY"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18390617-name-1444" type="given" value="JAMES"></interp>JAMES CROSSLEY</persName>
                  </hi>. I am the son of Henry Crossley, a currier, in Church-street, Deptford. On the 13th of May, the prisoner came and purchased some leather—my father was serving him, he had occasion to torn his back to serve another customer, and I saw the prisoner put this piece of leather into the basket which he had—he left the shop—I followed and gave him into custody of the policeman, who found the leather in his basket.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined by</hi> 
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. PATHS</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> Was he sober? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> Yes; he did not seem as if he had been drinking—I was at the back of the desk—I was in such a situation that I could see well, I was about fife yards from him—my father went out of the shop into the adjoining room—it is a long shop—when the leather was found be offered to pay for it—it was worth 1<hi rend="italic">s</hi>.</p>
               <p>
